          "body": "The rhetorical questions of vv.7-9 are among the sharpest in the book. 'Were you the first man to be born? Were you brought forth before the hills? Do you hear the secret counsel of God?' Each question attacks a different implied claim of Job's: primordial status, pre-creation existence, privileged divine access. The profound irony — invisible to Eliphaz — is that chapters 1-2 have placed the reader in precisely the divine council Eliphaz mocks. Job does not know what happened in that heavenly assembly, but the reader does. Eliphaz's sarcasm lands in a gap between what he knows and what the audience knows, and the sarcasm backfires. When Eliphaz appeals to the authority of the 'gray-haired and aged' who are older than Job's father (v.10), he is invoking an epistemological principle — accumulated traditional wisdom — that sounds unassailable. But Job's situation is precisely the case that breaks the traditional framework. The theological anthropology of vv.14-16 is technically orthodox — man is morally incapable before God, even angels are not pure in His sight — but Eliphaz deploys it as a closed trap: since no man can be righteous (v.14) and man drinks iniquity like water (v.16), Job's claim to integrity is structurally impossible. The doctrine of universal human sinfulness is weaponized against a specific person's specific claim."
